Sure, he=E2=80=99s right, but fashion is weird. You see this kind of intern=
al competition all the time within the groups in Europe. Kering, LVMH, and =
Richemont all price their different brands differently=E2=80=94some lower, =
some higher=E2=80=94to appeal to different segments of the market. That sai=
d, it=E2=80=99s embarrassing to everyone involved to keep calling a combine=
d Tapestry and Capri the =E2=80=9CLVMH of the U.S.=E2=80=9D (It was never g=
oing to portend that sort of dominance=E2=80=A6) And while I still believe =
that this was far too small a merger to invoke the ire of the F.T.C., I sus=
pect that their definition of =E2=80=9Caccessible luxury=E2=80=9D really me=
ans outlet-store luxury, which Coach (Tapestry) and Michael Kors (Capri) do=
 dominate=E2=80=94and would really dominate in partnership.

Capri=E2=80=99s stock nosedived 47 percent on Friday, while Tapestry=E2=80=
=99s
shares shot up 14 percent, perhaps reflecting the fact that many executives=
 are still in shock, while some claim they saw this coming. Now, the compan=
ies will appeal because the deal they struck requires them to do so. But it=
 won=E2=80=99t do anything, or course, and both companies will need to figu=
re out what=E2=80=99s next fairly quickly. Here=E2=80=99s what I=E2=80=99m =
hearing=E2=80=A6

The Biggest Loser

Let=E2=80=99s start with Capri: First off, condolences to group C.E.O. John=
 Idol, he of Kors-I.P.O. and Tommy Hilfiger-exit fame, who was supposed to =
retire years ago but hung on to pull off one last big deal. Now, there=E2=
=80=99s no way he stays and, ergo, no way Capri looks the same in 18 months=
=2E Jimmy Choo and Versace, the two sma=
ller brands in the portfolio, are like=
ly to sell quickly=E2=80=94for less than the cost that Capri acquired them =
but at a reasonable price nonetheless.

The biggest loser here is Michael Kors, which has fewer options. One close =
observer predicted it would go to a licensor, such as ABG or G-III, which o=
wns Donna Karan. Kors would be a large business for them to absorb, but als=
o a ubiquitous and valuable one. So the real condolences go out to Michael =
Kors, himself, who did everything right to maintain
the value of the ready-to-wear while his counterparts on the operations sid=
e missed out on several opportunities to take the business further upmarket=
=2E

Tapestry is in a stronger position due to its successful repositioning of C=
oach, which began a decade ago. Sure, the company still leans on off-price,=
 but it also sells handbags to young people in a convincing way=E2=80=94fro=
m the Tabby bag, originally an outlet-only style that eventually became a f=
ull-price hit, up to this Brooklyn hobo ( https://fave.co/4e6jnRd?utm_campa=
ign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F28%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io =
) that=E2=80=99s been trending on TikTok. That said, I don=E2=80=99t think =
Tapestry exists in its current form in a year and a half, either. The other=
 two brands in the portfolio=E2=80=94Kate Spade New York and Stuart Weitzma=
n=E2=80=94have languished, proving that the company doesn=E2=80=99t have th=
e executive talent to make things work across a
portfolio of three, let alone six.

